}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 22 "4.  Prime Numbers.  A " }{TEXT 281 12 "
prime number" }{TEXT -1 38 " is an integer (greater than 1 -- why " }
{TEXT 258 12 "greater than" }{TEXT -1 124 " 1?) for which the only (po
sitive integer) factors are 1 and itself.  Examples of prime numbers a
re: 2, 13, 101, 20110771.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "The Maple command " }{TEXT 259 7 "isprime" }
{TEXT -1 58 " determines whether or not a given integer is prime.  Use
 " }{TEXT 260 7 "isprime" }{TEXT -1 105 " it to determine whether  the
 following numbers are prime:  29,  35,  1537,  your ss#,   10!+1,  32
9891. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 50 "Find all of the prime numbers between 0 and 200.  " }
{TEXT 277 4 "Note" }{TEXT -1 63 ":  It will be helpful for you to revi
ew the information in the " }{TEXT 263 11 "programming" }{TEXT -1 15 "
 worksheet on  " }{TEXT 264 9 "for loops" }{TEXT -1 6 " and  " }{TEXT 
265 13 "if statements" }{TEXT -1 1 "." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 404 "N.B.  There are various \+
questions and properties about prime numbers which are of interest and
 study.  For example, it is known that there are infinitely many prime
s.  There is only one even prime. (Why?)  The distribution of the odd \+
primes is not fully understood.  If two consecutive odd numbers are bo
th prime (e.g., (5,7) ; (17,19), (101,103)), then such a pair of conse
cutive odd primes is called a " }{TEXT 282 19 "pair of twin primes" }
{TEXT -1 174 ".  It is not known whether or not there are infinitely m
any such pairs of twin primes.  It is known that there can be arbitrar
ily large gaps between consecutive primes.  Etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 372 "5.  Relatively Prime Num
bers.  Two positive integers are said to be relatively prime if the on
ly positive integer which (evenly) divides both of them is 1.  Example
s of  (pairs of) relatively prime integers are:  74, 51;   13, 120;   \+
344280, 267317.  If two integers are relatively prime, then the greate
st common divisor of the two integers must be 1.  The maple command " 
}{TEXT 278 3 "gcd" }{TEXT -1 296 " can be used to determine whether gr
eatest common divisor of two integers is 1, i.e., whether the two inte
gers are relatively prime.  Show that each of the above mentioned pair
s of integers are relatively prime.  Find three other pairs of relativ
ely prime integers with the following constraints:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 72 "(a) neither integer is itself prime; (b) each integer is \+
more than 1000." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 88 "List (once) each pair of integers from the range 1
00  to 110 that are relatively prime. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 3 "6. " }{TEXT 267 33 "Fundam
ental Theorem of Arithmetic" }{TEXT -1 148 ".  The Fundamental Theorem
 of Arithmetic states that every integer can be factored in a unique w
ay into a product of powers of primes.  For example:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "84 = " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "
``(2)^2*``(3)*``(7);" "6#*(-%!G6#\"\"#F'-F%6#\"\"$\"\"\"-F%6#\"\"(F+" 
}{TEXT -1 4 " ;  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 9 "28490 =  " }{XPPEDIT 
18 0 "``(2)*``(5)*``(7)*``(11)*``(37);" "6#*,-%!G6#\"\"#\"\"\"-F%6#\"
\"&F(-F%6#\"\"(F(-F%6#\"#6F(-F%6#\"#PF(" }{TEXT -1 4 " ;  " }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 21 "5813258142483000  =  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "``(2)^3*``
(3)^4*``(5)^3*``(11)^2*``(23)^3*``(29)*``(41)^2;" "6#*0-%!G6#\"\"#\"\"
$-F%6#F(\"\"%-F%6#\"\"&F(-F%6#\"#6F'-F%6#\"#BF(-F%6#\"#H\"\"\"-F%6#\"#
TF'" }{TEXT -1 4 " .  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 17 "It is called the " }{TEXT 270 11 "Fundamental" }
{TEXT -1 217 " Theorem of Arithmetic because of the role it plays in b
oth simple and deep results in algebra and number theory.  There are n
umerous and important facts which follow because of  the Fundamental T
heorem of Arithmetic." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 10 "          " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 111 "Use paper and pencil to factor the follo
wing integers into their prime decompositions:  340340, 38*865, 10!.  \+
 " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 266 8 "Answ
ers:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "T
he Maple command  " }{TEXT 268 7 "ifactor" }{TEXT -1 32 " does this au
tomatically.   Use " }{TEXT 269 7 "ifactor" }{TEXT -1 102 " to verify \+
your results from above.  Now factor the following numbers:  384*8650,
  10!+1 ,  your ss#. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "7.  Greatest Common Divisors and Least C
ommon Multiple (and the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic).  Maple can
 compute for a pair of integers (a,b) both the greatest common divisor
 of  (a,b) and the least common multiple of (a,b) easily.  The command
s for doing so are gcd(a,b) and lcm(a,b), respectively.  For each of t
he following pairs (a,b) find both the gcd(a,b) and the lcm(a,b)" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "a.  74,1
48           b.  201, 1001         c.  202, 1002     d.  2432902008176
640000,41758540970065920000" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 74 "For the pair of numbers 144 and 84 execute the \+
following command sequence:" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
33 "144=ifactor(144);\n84=ifactor(84);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 23 "144*84=ifactor(144*84);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 33 "gcd(144,84)=ifactor(gcd(144,84));" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 
"> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 33 "lcm(144,84)=ifactor(lcm(144,84));" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 57 "lcm(144,84)*gcd(144,84)=ifac
tor(lcm(144,84)*gcd(144,84));" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 82 "For the pair of numbers 2744280 and 26730
0 execute the following command sequence:" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 49 "2744280=ifactor(2744280);\n267300=ifactor(267300);" }
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 39 "2744280*267300=ifactor(274
4280*267300);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 49 "gcd(274428
0,267300)=ifactor(gcd(2744280,267300));" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 49 "lcm(2744280,267300)=ifactor(lcm(2744280,267300));" }}
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 89 "lcm(2744280,267300)*gcd(274
4280,267300)=ifactor(lcm(2744280,267300)*gcd(2744280,267300));" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 11 "You assig
n " }{TEXT 272 2 "a " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }{TEXT 283 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 
88 " to be any pair of numbers (positive integers).  Execute the follo
wing command sequence:" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "a \+
:= ;\nb := ;" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 28 "a=ifactor(a
);\nbb=ifactor(b);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 17 "a*b=i
factor(a*b);" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "gcd(a,b)=if
actor(gcd(a,b));" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "lcm(a,b
)=ifactor(lcm(a,b));" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 45 "lcm
(a,b)*gcd(a,b)=ifactor(lcm(a,b)*gcd(a,b));" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
